A fun puzzle game with a unique time-shifting mechanism. The puzzles are fun without being overly hard (for the most part). While the game is fairly short, I enjoyed it. Though it is sad how low-res the Android version is compared to a console version -- I played on a tablet and the characters rendered at something near SNES res (the backgrounds render better than the foregrounds).
Such simple mechanics for the game, yet such diversity in levels and solutions to puzzles. It was refreshingly different and just the right balance of difficulty.

My gosh this game is so beautiful. Thank you so much for this creative and heartwarming game!! I just loved the sweet storyline and the music is gorgeous. But I really love this game. :-) This game is child friendly, and adults can play it too.

content: Ridiculous!! I installed this game thinking it'd be really unique & a cool game. And who knows... Maybe it is. But there's barely any instruction & no hints to help out! I uninstalled it after 15 minutes of trying to figure out what the hell the objective is! Good luck!!
replyContent: Hey Rey, It's a fair criticism. The game is designed to be super minimal, perhaps too minimal? The goal is to find the light in each garden and take it to the top of each island where you can place it in the beacon. Each island represents a specific memory from their friendship as it bloomed. I hope that helps.

This is what I call a "game as an experience" - those looking for the most difficult gameplay/puzzles will unlikely be satisfied, but they miss the mark when looking at a game like this in that lens. I won't judge others, but to me, anyone can create a puzzle. Few can create a genuine experience through a medium such as video games - especially that translate well on mobile. It's a beautiful, sincere, thoughtful game with charming art/animation style, soundtrack, and intuitive gameplay. 5/5 üëç

Beautiful, at times touching, but the puzzles are a bit repetitive and it could use some exposition. Having such a limited set of controls is an interesting take... I'm unsure whether I like that or not
replyContent: Hey Nick, thanks for the feedback! You've touched on some goals we've had from day one; simple and intuitive controls with the depth in the puzzles not the input, and to have an internationally approachable game with no words, text or speech. That was all very intentional. The goal was to tell a story within those constraints. Hope that helps.

content: This game is beautiful. Once you figure out what each strange object does it's alot of fun. a challenge as well. Thanks to developers...this game is going to on all my devices

This game has some monument valley vibes imo. It is very unique though! The controls are perfect for mobile phones, the game can easily be played with one finger. The game is very fine graphics wise, but who wants to experience the great atmosphere to the fullest needs to play with sound on, preferably with headphones! Definitely a recommendation by me, for everyone who is looking for a relaxing experience.

replyContent:
No background story? Did you see the intro cutscene? Arina and Frendt are in their treehouse during a stormy night when a magical light appears, transporting them to a mysterious and surreal place. Seems like a story to me!
EDIT: Fair enough. I will say the puzzles do get much harder and more interesting later. But its not for everyone. Thx Jack.
